#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:8
#, no-c-format
msgid "Managing multipath I/O for devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:15
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This section describes how to manage failover and path load balancing for "
"multiple paths between the servers and block storage devices by using "
"Multipath I/O (MPIO)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:21
#, no-c-format
msgid "Understanding multipath I/O"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:23
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Multipathing is the ability of a server to communicate with the same "
"physical or logical block storage device across multiple physical paths "
"between the host bus adapters in the server and the storage controllers for "
"the device, typically in Fibre Channel (FC) or iSCSI SAN environments."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:30
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Linux multipathing provides connection fault tolerance and can provide load "
"balancing across the active connections. When multipathing is configured and "
"running, it automatically isolates and identifies device connection "
"failures, and reroutes I/O to alternate connections."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:37
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Multipathing provides fault tolerance against connection failures, but not "
"against failures of the storage device itself. The latter is achieved with "
"complementary techniques like mirroring."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:45
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath terminology"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:48
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Storage array\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t A hardware device with many disks and multiple\t fabrics connections "
"(controllers) that provides SAN or NAS storage\t to clients. Storage arrays "
"typically have RAID and failover\t features and support multipathing. "
"Historically,\t active/passive (failover) and active/active\t (load-"
"balancing) storage array configurations were\t distinguished. These concepts "
"still exist but they are merely\t special cases of the concepts of path "
"groups and access\t states supported by modern hardware.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Host, host system\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:70
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The computer running &productname; which acts as a client system\t for a "
"<emphasis>storage array</emphasis> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:77
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Multipath map, multipath device\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:81
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t A set of <emphasis>path devices</emphasis> . It represents a\t storage "
"volume on a storage array and is seen as\t a single block device by the host "
"system.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:89
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Path device, low-level device\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:93
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t A member of a multipath map, typically a SCSI device.\t Each path device "
"represents a unique\t connection between the host computer and the actual "
"storage\t volume, for example, a logical unit from an iSCSI session.\t Under "
"Linux device mapper multipath, path devices remain visible\t and accessible "
"in the host system.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:104
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t WWID, UID, UUID\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:108
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t &ldquo;World Wide Identifier&rdquo;, &ldquo;Unique\t Identifier&rdquo;, "
"&ldquo;Universally Unique Identifier&rdquo;.\t The WWID is a property\t of "
"the storage volume and as such, it is identical between all path\t devices "
"of a multipath map. <filename>multipath-tools</filename> \t uses the WWID to"
"\t determine which low-level devices should be assembled into a\t multipath "
"map. multipath relies on <command>udev</command> to\t determine the WWID of "
"path devices. The WWID of a multipath map never\t changes. multipath devices "
"can be reliably accessed through\t <filename>/dev/disk/by-id/dm-uuid-mpath-"
"<replaceable>WWID</replaceable></filename> .\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:121
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t The WWID should be distinguished from the <emphasis>map\t name</"
"emphasis> , which is configurable (see\t <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-names"
"\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ).\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:129
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t uevent, udev event\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:133
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t An event sent by the kernel to user space and processed by the\t "
"<command>udev</command> subsystem. Uevents are generated when\t devices are "
"added, removed, or change their properties.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:141
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t Device mapper\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:145
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t A framework in the Linux kernel for creating virtual block\t devices. I/O "
"operations to mapped devices are redirected to\t the underlying block "
"devices. Device mappings may be\t stacked. The device mapper implements its "
"own event signaling,\t also known as &ldquo;device mapper events&rdquo;\t or "
"&ldquo;dm events&rdquo;.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:159
#, no-c-format
msgid "Hardware support"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:161
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The multipathing drivers and tools are available on all architectures "
"supported by &productname;. The generic, protocol-agnostic driver works with "
"most multipath-capable storage hardware on the market. Some storage array "
"vendors provide their own multipathing management tools. Consult the "
"vendor’s hardware documentation to determine what settings are required."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:171
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath implementations: device mapper and NVMe"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:173
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The traditional, generic implementation of multipathing under Linux uses the "
"device mapper framework. For most device types like SCSI devices, device "
"mapper multipathing is the only available implementation. Device mapper "
"multipathing is highly configurable and flexible."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:180
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Linux <emphasis>NVM Express</emphasis> (NVMe) kernel subsystem "
"implements multipathing natively in the kernel. This implementation creates "
"less computational overhead for NVMe devices, which are typically fast "
"devices with very low latencies. Native NVMe multipathing requires no user "
"space component. Since &slea; 15, native multipathing has been the default "
"for NVMe multipath devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:188
#, no-c-format
msgid "The rest of this chapter is about device mapper multipath."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:194
#, no-c-format
msgid "Storage array autodetection for multipathing"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:195
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Device mapper multipath is a generic technology. Multipath device detection "
"requires only that the low-level (for example, SCSI) devices are detected by "
"the kernel, and that device properties reliably identify multiple low-level "
"devices as being different &ldquo;paths&rdquo; to the same volume rather "
"than actually different devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:203
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <filename>multipath-tools</filename> package detects storage arrays by "
"their vendor and product names. It has validated built-in configuration "
"defaults for a large variety of storage products. Consult the hardware "
"documentation of your storage array; some vendors provide specific "
"recommendations for Linux multipathing configuration. To see the built-in "
"settings for storage that has been detected on your system, run the command "
"<command>multipath -T</command> , see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-"
"mpiotools-multipath\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:214
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you need to apply changes to the built-in configuration for your storage "
"array, create and configure the <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> "
"file. See <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-conf-file\" xrefstyle="
"\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:221
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<filename>multipath-tools</filename> has built-in presets for many storage "
"arrays. The existence of such presets for a given storage product "
"<emphasis>does not imply</emphasis> that the vendor of the storage product "
"has tested the product with <systemitem>dm-multipath</systemitem> , nor that "
"the vendor endorses or supports use of <systemitem>dm-multipath</systemitem> "
"with the product. Always consult the original vendor documentation for "
"support-related questions."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:236
#, no-c-format
msgid "Storage arrays that require specific hardware handlers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:237
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Some storage arrays require special commands for failover from one path to "
"the other, or non-standard error handling methods. These special commands "
"and methods are implemented by hardware handlers in the Linux kernel. Modern "
"SCSI storage arrays support the &ldquo;Asymmetric Logical Unit Access&rdquo; "
"(ALUA) hardware handler defined in the SCSI standard. Besides ALUA, the "
"&slea; kernel contains hardware handlers for Netapp E-Series (RDAC), the "
"Dell/EMC CLARiiON CX family of arrays, and legacy arrays from HP. Since "
"Linux kernel 4.4, the Linux kernel has automatically detected hardware "
"handlers for most arrays, including all arrays supporting ALUA."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:252
#, no-c-format
msgid "Planning for multipathing"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:254
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Use the guidelines in this section when planning your multipath I/O solution."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:260
#, no-c-format
msgid "Prerequisites"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:263
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The storage array you use for the multipathed device must support "
"multipathing. For more information, see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-"
"hardware\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:270
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You need to configure multipathing only if multiple physical paths exist "
"between host bus adapters in the server and host bus controllers for the "
"block storage device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:277
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For some storage arrays, the vendor provides its own multipathing software "
"to manage multipathing for the array’s physical and logical devices. In this "
"case, you should follow the vendor’s instructions for configuring "
"multipathing for those devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:285
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"When using multipathing in a virtualization environment, the multipathing is "
"controlled in the host server environment. Configure multipathing for the "
"device before you assign it to a virtual guest machine."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:295
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath installation types and the initramfs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:297
#, no-c-format
msgid "Root file system on multipath (SAN-boot)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:298
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\tThe root file system is on a multipath device (usually,\tall other file "
"systems are on multipath storage as well).\tThis is typically the case for"
"\tdiskless servers that use SAN or NAS storage exclusively. On such"
"\tsystems, multipath support is required for booting, and multipathing\tmust "
"be enabled in the initramfs (initrd).\tSee <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-"
"initrd-sync\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:309
#, no-c-format
msgid "Root file system on a local disk"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:310
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\tThe root file system (and possibly some other file systems) is in local"
"\tstorage, for example, on a directly attached SATA disk or local RAID,\tbut "
"the system additionally uses file systems in the multipath SAN or NAS"
"\tstorage. This system type can be configured in three different ways:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:318
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using a root-on-multipath setup"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:321
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t \t All block devices are part of multipath maps, including the local disk."
"\t Such a setup then appears as a degraded multipath map with just one\t "
"path. This configuration is created if multipathing was enabled during\t the "
"initial system installation with &yast;. It is the simplest\t configuration "
"but has a performance overhead.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:332
#, no-c-format
msgid "Ignoring the local disk by <systemitem>multipath-tools</systemitem>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:334
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t In this configuration, multipathing is enabled in the initramfs.\t \t "
"This configuration can be achieved after the installation by \t "
"blacklisting, or with the\t <literal>find_multipaths</literal> configuration "
"parameter.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
#: storage_multipath.xml:344
#, no-c-format
msgid "Disabling multipathing in the initramfs"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:346
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t This setup is created if multipathing was not enabled during \t the "
"initial system installation with &yast;, either because \t &yast; did not "
"detect multipath devices or because the \t user opted against enabling "
"multipath during installation.\t This is the only situation in which\t <xref "
"linkend=\"sec-multipath-initrd-sync\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> does "
"not apply.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:358
#, no-c-format
msgid "\t\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:364
#, no-c-format
msgid "Keeping the initial RAM disk synchronized"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:366
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\t Make sure\t that the initial RAM disk and the booted system behave "
"consistently\t regarding the use of multipathing for all block devices.\t "
"Rebuild the initramfs after applying multipath configuration\t changes.\t"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:374
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If multipathing is enabled in the system, it also needs to be enabled in the "
"<filename>initramfs</filename> and vice versa. The only exception to this "
"rule is the option <xref linkend=\"vl-multipath-planning-type-noroot-noinitrd"
"\"/> in <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-planning-type-noroot\" xrefstyle="
"\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:382
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The multipath configuration must be synchronized between the booted system "
"and the initrd. Therefore, if <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> , "
"<filename>/etc/multipath/wwids</filename> , <filename>/etc/multipath/"
"bindings</filename> , or other configuration file or udev rules related to "
"device identification are changed, the initial RAM FS needs to be rebuilt "
"using the command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:390
#, no-c-format
msgid "&prompt.sudo;dracut -f"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:391
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If the <filename>initrd</filename> and the system are not synchronized, the "
"system will not properly boot and the start-up procedure may result in an "
"emergency shell. See <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-trouble-root\"/> for "
"instructions on how to avoid or repair such a scenario."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:397
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Special care must be taken if the initial RAM disk is rebuilt in non-"
"standard situations, for example, from a rescue system or after booting with "
"the kernel parameter <literal>multipath=off</literal> . <command>dracut</"
"command> will automatically include multipathing support in the initial RAM "
"disk if and only if it detects that the root file system is on a multipath "
"device while the initrd is being built. In such cases, it is necessary to "
"enable or disable multipathing explicitly."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:407
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To enable multipath support in the <filename>initrd</filename> , run the "
"command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:410
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"&prompt.sudo;dracut --force --add multipath\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:413
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"To disable multipath support in <filename>initrd</filename> , run the "
"command:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: storage_multipath.xml:416
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"\n"
"&prompt.sudo;dracut --force --omit multipath\n"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:422
#, no-c-format
msgid "Disk management tasks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:423
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Use third-party SAN array management tools or the user interface of your "
"storage array to create logical devices and assign them to hosts. Make sure "
"to configure the host credentials correctly on both sides."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:428
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"You can add or remove volumes to a running host, but detecting the changes "
"may require rescanning SCSI targets and reconfiguring multipathing on the "
"host."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:436
#, no-c-format
msgid "Software RAID and complex storage stacks"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:437
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Multipathing is set up on top of basic storage devices such as SCSI disks. "
"In a multi-layered storage stack, multipathing is always the bottom layer. "
"Other layers such as software RAID, Logical Volume Management, block device "
"encryption, etc. are layered on top of it. Therefore, for each device that "
"has multiple I/O paths and that you plan to use in a software RAID, you must "
"configure the device for multipathing before you attempt to create the "
"software RAID device."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:449
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For information about setting up multipathing for existing software RAIDs, "
"see <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-raid\" xrefstyle=\"SectTitleOnPage\"/> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:456
#, no-c-format
msgid "High-availability solutions"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:457
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"High-availability solutions for clustering storage resources run on top of "
"the multipathing service on each node. Make sure that the configuration "
"settings in the <filename>/etc/multipath.conf</filename> file on each node "
"are consistent across the cluster."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:463
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Make sure that multipath devices have the same name across all devices. "
"Refer to <xref linkend=\"sec-multipath-names-ha\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:467
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Distributed Replicated Block Device (DRBD) high-availability solution "
"for mirroring devices across a LAN runs on top of multipathing. For each "
"device that has multiple I/O paths and that you plan to use in a DRDB "
"solution, you must configure the device for multipathing before you "
"configure DRBD."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:474
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Special care must be taken when using multipathing together with clustering "
"software that relies on shared storage for fencing, such as "
"<command>pacemaker</command> with <command>sbd</command> . See <xref linkend="
"\"sec-multipath-policies-default\"/> for details."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:483
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath management tools"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:485
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The multipathing support in &productname; is based on the Device Mapper "
"Multipath module of the Linux kernel and the <systemitem>multipath-tools</"
"systemitem> user space package. You can use the Multiple Devices "
"Administration utility ( <command>multipath</command> ) to view the status "
"of multipathed devices."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:494
#, no-c-format
msgid "Device mapper multipath module"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:495
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The Device Mapper Multipath (DM-MP) module provides the generic multipathing "
"capability for Linux. DM-MPIO is the preferred solution for multipathing on "
"&productname; for SCSI and DASD devices, and can be used for NVMe devices as "
"well."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:502
#, no-c-format
msgid "Using DM-MP for NVMe devices"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:503
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Since &productname; 15, native NVMe multipathing (see <xref linkend=\"sec-"
"multipath-hardware-implementations\"/> ) has been recommended for NVMe and "
"used by default. To disable native NVMe multipathing and use device mapper "
"multipath instead, boot with the kernel parameter <literal>nvme-core."
"multipath=0</literal> ."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:512
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"DM-MPIO features automatic configuration of the multipathing subsystem for a "
"large variety of setups."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:516
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The multipath daemon <command>multipathd</command> takes care of automatic "
"path discovery and grouping, and automated path retesting, so that a "
"previously failed path is automatically reinstated when it becomes healthy "
"again. This minimizes the need for administrator attention in a production "
"environment."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:523
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"DM-MPIO protects against failures in the paths to the device, and not "
"failures in the device itself. If one of the active paths is lost (for "
"example, a network adapter breaks or a fiber-optic cable is removed), I/O is "
"redirected to the remaining paths. If all active paths fail, inactive "
"secondary paths must be woken up, so failover occurs with a delay of up to "
"30 seconds, depending on the properties of the storage array."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:531
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If every path to a given device has failed, I/O to this device can be queued "
"in the kernel, either for a given amount of time or even indefinitely (in "
"which case the total amount of queued IO is limited by system memory)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:537
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If a disk array has more than one storage processor, ensure that the SAN "
"switch has a connection to the storage processor that owns the LUNs you want "
"to access. On most disk arrays, all LUNs belong to both storage processors, "
"so both connections are active."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:544
#, no-c-format
msgid "Storage processors"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:545
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"On some disk arrays, the storage array manages the traffic through storage "
"processors so that it presents only one storage processor at a time. One "
"processor is active and the other one is passive until there is a failure. "
"If you are connected to the wrong storage processor (the one with the "
"passive path) you might not see the expected LUNs, or you might see the LUNs "
"but get errors when you try to access them."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: storage_multipath.xml:557
#, no-c-format
msgid "Multipath I/O management tools"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: storage_multipath.xml:558
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The packages <systemitem class=\"resource\">multipath-tools</systemitem> and "
"<systemitem class=\"resource\">kpartx</systemitem> provide tools that take "
"care of automatic path discovery and grouping."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: term
